  "prompt": "Why is there so little research on maladaptive daydreaming?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why research on maladaptive daydreaming (MD) is limited:\n\n1. Relatively new concept\n- The term was first coined in 2002 by Professor Eli Zelterman\n- Not yet recognized as an official psychiatric disorder in diagnostic manuals\n\n2. Limited scientific understanding\n- Lack of clear diagnostic criteria\n- Unclear neurological and psychological mechanisms\n- Difficulty in measuring and quantifying the experience\n\n3. Research challenges\n- Relies primarily on self-reporting\n- No standardized assessment tools\n- Overlaps with other conditions like ADHD, dissociative disorders\n- Difficulty recruiting participants and studying the phenomenon\n\n4. Academic and clinical skepticism\n- Not considered a formal mental health disorder\n- Some researchers view it as a symptom rather than a distinct condition\n- Limited funding and academic interest\n\n5. Stigma and low awareness\n- Many people are unaware the condition exists\n- Individuals may feel embarrassed or hesitant to discuss their experiences\n- Limited public discourse and recognition\n\n6. Complex nature of the experience\n- Highly individual and subjective experience\n- Varies significantly between individuals\n- Challenging to generalize research findings\n\nThese factors contribute to the current lack of comprehensive research on maladaptive daydreaming.",
